#Text=Thirteen Martyrs of Cavite

#Text=The Thirteen Martyrs of Cavite ( Tagalog : Labintatlong Martir ng Kabite ; Spanish : Trece Mártires de Cavite ) were Filipino patriots in Cavite , Philippines who were executed by musketry on September 12 , 1896 , for cooperating with the Katipunan during the Philippine Revolution against Spain .
#Text=The de facto capital city of Trece Martires in Cavite is named after them .
#Text=The Thirteen Martyrs Monument along Governor 's Drive in Trece Martires , Cavite erected in 2004 .
#Text=The Martyrs
#Text=The historical marker of the monument in Trece Martires , Cavite
#Text=The Cavite Conspiracy

#Text=Shortly before the Katipunan was uncovered , Emilio Aguinaldo was planning to attack the Spanish arsenal at Fort San Felipe and he enlisted other Katipuneros to recruit enough men so they could overrun the Spanish garrison .
#Text=Their meetings were held at the house of Cabuco .
#Text=Aguinaldo and the other Katipuneros agreed that they would arm the inmates of the provincial jail who were made to work at the garrison .
#Text=The task of recruiting the inmates was given to Lapidario , who was also the warden of the provincial jail .
#Text=Aguado was to supply Lapidario with money to buy arms .
#Text=According to their plan , the uprising would be signalled by fireworks from the warehouse of Inocencio .
#Text=Other leaders of the uprising were Luciano , Conchu , Pérez , Pablo José , Marcos José , and Juan Castañeda .
#Text=The revolt was to start on September 1 .

#Text=On August 26 , Aguinaldo received a letter from Andrés Bonifacio who reported that a Katipunan assembly in Balintawak on August 24 decided to start the revolution on August 30 , to be signalled by a blackout at the Luneta , then known as Bagumbayan .
#Text=On the appointed day , Bonifacio and his men attacked the Spanish powder magazine in San Juan .
#Text=Later that same day , the Spanish authorities declared martial law in Manila and the provinces of Cavite , Laguna , Batangas , Bulacan , Pampanga , Tarlac and Nueva Ecija .
#Text=Aguinaldo learned of the declaration of martial law in a meeting with Spanish Governor Fernando Pargas on the morning of August 31 , 1896 .
#Text=He then went to Cabezas ' haberdashery and ask him to inform to Lapidario that they had alternative but to rise in arms .
#Text=Cabezas was the one who enlisted Lapidario for the planned uprising .
#Text=But Cabezas was not in favor of starting the revolt on August 31 , 1896 so they discussed the uprising further .
#Text=They decided to postpone the attack to September 3 .
#Text=However , the Spanish learned of the plan from a dressmaker named Victoriana Sayat and they immediately arrested Lapidario , de Ocampo and Aguado .
#Text=The three were held incommunicado in the boat Ulloa and interrogated .
#Text=They are presumed to have been tortured .
#Text=The Thirteen Martyrs Monument in San Roque

#Text=De Ocampo revealed the names of his companions and the thirteen suspects were rounded up on September 3 along with dozens of other Cavite leaders , including the musician Julián Felipe , who would compose the Philippine national anthem the following year .
#Text=Felipe was incarcerated for nine months at Fort San Felipe .
#Text=Also subsequently released were Pablo and Marcos José , and Juan Castañeda of Imus , who are also believed to have been involved in the uprising .
#Text=While awaiting trial , guilt-stricken de Ocampo tried to commit suicide by slashing his stomach with a piece of broken glass .
#Text=However , he was included in the indictment for treason before a military court which found them guilty on September 11 after a four-hour trial .
#Text=At 12:45p . m. the following day , the thirteen patriots were brought out of their cells and taken to the Plaza de Armas , outside Fort San Felipe , and executed by musketry .
#Text=Their bodies were later buried in a common grave at the Catholic cemetery at the village of Caridad .

#Text=Later , the bodies of seven of the martyrs — Máximo Inocencio , Victorino Luciano , Francisco Osorio , Luis Aguado , Hugo Pérez , José Lallana , and Antonio San Agustín — were exhumed and reburied elsewhere .
#Text=But the rest — Agapito Conchu , Máximo Gregorio , Alfonso de Ocampo , Eugenio Cabezas , Feliciano Cabuco , and Severino Lapidario remained unclaimed in their common grave .
#Text=In 1906 , a monument to the Thirteen Martyrs was erected at the San Roque district of Cavite City , at the head of then San Roque causeway .
#Text=Their families reinterred the remains of their loved ones at the foot of the monument .
#Text=The monument is located at the intersection of M. Valentin St. , Lopez Jaena Rd , Zulueta Rd and the P. Burgos Ave.
#Text=Legacy
#Text=In 1954 , the capital of Cavite was transferred to a newly created city situated near the center of the province , and it was named Trece Mártires in their honor .
#Text=Each of its 13 barangays were named for each of the martyrs .
#Text=On May 24 , 2004 , a new monument of the thirteen patriots were inaugurated in Trece Martires near the City Hall .
